        <title><m>\S 2.1</m>: Vectors and Linear Combinations</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".25in">
                    <title>Motivation: Vectors</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							We've seen that computations with matrices of the form
							<me>
								\left[
								\begin{array}{rrr|r}
								1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
								-3 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
								2 \amp 3 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
								\end{array}
								\right]
							</me>
							can help us solve linear systems. In this chapter, we'll try to understand the geometric
							(visual) information held in these matrices to further our understanding of linear systems.
						</p>
					</solution>
                    
                </exercise>

